cff_blend_doBlend( CFF_SubFont  subFont,
                    CFF_Parser   parser,
                    FT_UInt      numBlends )
{
  ...
  size = 5 * numBlends;
  if ( subFont->blend_used + size > subFont->blend_alloc )
  {
    /* VULNERABLE: no save of old blend_stack pointer, no adjustment
       of parser->stack entries after FT_REALLOC moves the buffer */
    if ( FT_REALLOC( subFont->blend_stack,
                      subFont->blend_alloc,
                      subFont->blend_alloc + size ) )
      goto Exit;
    subFont->blend_top    = subFont->blend_stack + subFont->blend_used;
    subFont->blend_alloc += size;
  }
  subFont->blend_used += size;
  ...
  for ( i = 0; i < numBlends; i++ )
  {
    ...
    parser->stack[i + base] = subFont->blend_top;   /* stale after 2nd blend */
    *subFont->blend_top++             = 255;
    *((FT_UInt32*)subFont->blend_top) = (FT_UInt32)sum;
    subFont->blend_top               += 4;
  }
  ...
}
```

Expected crash: Heap-use-after-free READ (1 byte) in cff_blend_doBlend() (src/cff/cffload.c), reached via cff_parser_run -> cff_load_private_dict while parsing a CFF Private DICT with two or more consecutive `blend` operators. Each blend op may need to grow subFont->blend_stack via FT_REALLOC; when realloc moves the buffer, blend_top is correctly reset, but parser->stack entries from a *previous* blend op in the same DICT still point into the old (now-freed) allocation. A second blend op in a row reads through one of those stale parser->stack pointers, hitting freed heap memory. Fix adjusts every parser->stack pointer that fell inside the old buffer by the realloc's address delta.

